<subSubSection id="0BB6654CFFC9FF9EFF6941F9FE1BFAE9" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="431336C7FFC9FF9EFF6941F9FE1BFAE9" blockId="30.[151,1437,151,1463]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="71D8EAD5FFC9FF9EFF6941F9FEEDFB58" bold="true" box="[199,335,1152,1177]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="84AC4D44FFC9FF9EFEF641F8FDEEFB59" box="[344,588,1152,1176]" class="Insecta" family="Leucospidae" genus="Leucospis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opalescens">
<emphasis id="71D8EAD5FFC9FF9EFEF641F8FDEEFB59" box="[344,588,1152,1176]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Leucospis opalescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an endemic Brazilian species, which was previously recorded from the Amazon and Pantanal. The new records presented here extends its distribution southwestward to the Brazilian Savannah (
<figureCitation id="DB972A42FFC9FF9EFEBC41BEFECBFB21" box="[274,361,1223,1248]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1890,1912]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,526,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@40.[151,1436,526,1869]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 25. Geographic records of Leucospis in Brazil, based on literature." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1298019/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Figs 25</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="DB972A42FFC9FF9EFEDB41BEFE37FB21" box="[373,405,1223,1248]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="41.[151,250,1665,1687]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,195,1636]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[177,1411,195,1636]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURE 26. New geographic records of Leucospis in Brazil A. Detail of the state of Minas Gerais. B. New records in Brazil." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1298021/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">26</figureCitation>
). The presence of the lateral posterior projection of tergite VI in 
<taxonomicName id="84AC4D44FFC9FF9EFBC741B0FAA3FB21" box="[1129,1281,1224,1248]" class="Insecta" family="Leucospidae" genus="Leucospis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opalescens">
<emphasis id="71D8EAD5FFC9FF9EFBC741B0FAA3FB21" box="[1129,1281,1224,1248]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">L. opalescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females (
<figureCitation id="DB972A42FFC9FF9EFAC041BEFF1CFAC5" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1908,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,243,1855]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[151,1436,243,1855]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leucospis opalescens ♀ A. Habitus, lateral view. B. Habitus, dorsal view. C. Forewing. D. Forewing, stigma region in detail. E. Hind wing. F. Head, frontal view. G. Head and mesossoma, dorsal view. H. Scutellum, dorsellum and propodeum, postero-dorsal view. I. Hind leg, lateral view. J. Posterior region of metasoma, lateral view. Arrow shows a spiniform projection on sixth tergite. Scale bar = 1 mm. UFMG–IHY–1305651" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1298005/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 18J</figureCitation>
) is a valuable character for differentiating it from females of 
<taxonomicName id="84AC4D44FFC9FF9EFC3C4195FBB5FAC5" authorityName="Boucek" authorityYear="1974" box="[914,1047,1260,1284]" class="Insecta" family="Leucospidae" genus="Leucospis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="signifera">
<emphasis id="71D8EAD5FFC9FF9EFC3C4195FBB5FAC5" box="[914,1047,1260,1284]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">L. signifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a separation that was previously difficult (
<bibRefCitation id="273D4B36FFC9FF9EFF514076FE0FFAE9" box="[255,429,1295,1320]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" refId="ref24347" refString="Boucek, Z. (1974 a) A revision of the Leucospidae (Hymenoptera: Chalcidoidea) of the world. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Entomology, 23 (Supplement), 1 - 241." type="journal article">Bouček, 1974a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
